<H3> <TI>   Qian Meets Delegation, Views Statement on DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Qian Meets Delegation, Views Statement on DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0304105694 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 3 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0304105694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Toshiaki Arai] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 2 April -- Issei Inoue, deputy chairman of 
the Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ], and other members 
of the SDPJ delegation which is visiting China met with Chinese 
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen on 2 April and exchanged opinions 
on the DPRK nuclear issue. Foreign Minister Qian appraised 
positively the fact that the UN Security Council [UNSC] adopted 
the chairman's mildly worded statement rather than hinting at 
the possibility of imposing sanctions on the DPRK in the future. 
He said, "It helped to ease tension on the Korean peninsula and 
gave (the people concerned some leeway in terms of time to 
settle the issue peacefully)." 
  Foreign Minister Qian also touched on China's influence on 
North Korea and pointed out, "Like Japan, China is not a party 
[directly] concerned." In this way, he reminded the 
delegation's members not to expect too much. As has been said 
before, he insisted on a settlement through dialogue between the 
four parties: the United States, the DPRK, the ROK, and the 
International Atomic Energy Agency. 

</TEXT>

