<H3> <TI>   SDPJ's Kubo Disappointed With PRC Reaction to DPRK Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDPJ's Kubo Disappointed With PRC Reaction to DPRK Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705093494 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 17 
May 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1705093494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Kimihiko Yoshida; from NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 17 May </F>
Morning Edition] 
  [Text] Beijing -- Wataru Kubo, secretary general of the 
Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ], held a news conference 
after holding talks with Li Shuzheng, head of the CPC 
International Liaison Department, on 16 May. Giving a bitter 
smile, Kubo said: "There has been no major change since April of 
last year when an SDPJ delegation visited China." He made the 
remarks because, although Kubo called on China to actively serve 
as a mediator in the issue of DPRK's (North Korea's) suspected 
nuclear arms development, he failed to get a satisfactory 
reaction from Li, as the SDPJ delegation did last year. On the 
contrary, Li admonished Kubo, stating that "putting pressure 
will heighten the tension." It seems that Kubo -- who 
persistently maintained the need "to cooperate with China" in 
dealing with the North Korea issue in previous policy 
consultations of the ruling coalition -- was disappointed with 
China's reaction. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

