<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dalai Lama Speaks on Beijing's Infringement of Human Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dalai Lama Speaks on Beijing's Infringement of Human Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1604012394 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 15 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1604012394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In an interview with an ASAHI SHIMBUN correspondent 
at a hotel near Narita Air Port on 14 April, the Dalai Lama, 58, 
a paramount Tibetan religious and political leader, stated: 
"China has trampled human rights in Tibet. I hope Japan and 
other nations will put pressure on China to halt the 
infringement of human rights in Tibet." The Tibetan religions 
leader granted the interview during his brief half-day stopover 
in Japan on his way to the United States for a meeting with 
American scientists. 
  In the interview, the Dalai Lama stressed there is no change 
in his position stressed in the 1988 Strasburg proposal that he 
does not seek complete the independence of Tibet, and will allow 
China to retain its power to handle Tibet's foreign and defense 
policies. In the interview, he candidly admitted that the 
Chinese Government has yet to make any positive response to his 
proposal. 
  Asked who will succeed the Panchen Lama, the Buddhist leader 
in Tibet who ranks 2nd only to the Dalai Lama in the Tibetan 
Buddhist hierarchy, the Tibetan religious leader said he has a 
list of candidates compiled by China and which contains five 
candidates. During the interview, he disclosed that he asked the 
Chinese Government to choose a successor to the Panchen Lama 
based on traditional methods, not on political reasons. He also 
proposed sending a survey team to that end, but the Chinese 
Government has rejected his request. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

